<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-944  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 944.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  April 2 1990 n294 p57(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC rejects Ameritech tariff proposal. (Federal CommunicationsCommission)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Casatelli, Christine.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Federal Communications Commission rejects a special accesstariff filed by Ameritech for the Chicago market.andP;  The proposalcalled for the provision of T1 and DS-3 communications service atprices lower than those mandated for the area.andP;  Ameritech's FiberHub Servicing Area concept called for customers of its IllinoisBell Telephone Co subsidiary to bypass the central officetransport network and transmit to a fiber optic hub.andP;  In so doing,they would have avoided a transmission stop and DS-3 mileagecosts, saving up to $1,150 per month on data transmission costs.andO;The plan was contested by Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc, whichoperates a dedicated fiber optic point-to-point transmissionservice in the area.andP;  MFS objected that the tariff's lack ofmileage charges would give Ameritech an unfair competitiveadvantage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Information Technologies Corp. (cases)Metropolitan Fiber Systems Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    AIT.andO;Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionTariffCommunications Service SuppliersT1 CommunicationsGovernment RegulationData CommunicationsCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>